What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The Data is structured as a list of 113936 rows each a individual loan with 81 different columns that represent different features of the the loans

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

The main columns I want to focus on are Borrower APR which is the amount interest on the loan.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

Other Features I want to explore are prosper rating, estimated return and Credit Score Upper Limit. For these I want to look at their relationship with Borrower APR

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

I looked at the distribution of Borrower APR, Prosper Rating and Estimated Return. Over 3600 of the loans appear to have a Borrower APR of .35797. Both Estimated Return and Borrower APR appear to have very similar distbutions with slight right skew.

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

Both the Borrower APR and Estimated Return distribution appear to have a slight right skew. I also created new dataframes that hold the Borrower APR, current deliquencies, Prosper Rating and credit score upper.

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

It appears that the the higher the credit score, the more likely the loan is to have a high prosper score and a lower Borrower APR. There does not seem to be a very strong relationship between higher credit score and a high return

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

I do find it interesting that a higher credit score does not lead to higher returns. But it does appear to lead to less variability in estimated return.
